                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On September 2, President <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> issued Executive Order 10483 establishing the
                    Operations Coordinating Board. In a simultaneous press release, the White House
                    announced that the Board <pb facs="0923" n="1737" xml:id="pg_1737"/> was an
                    interagency group designed “to provide for the integrated implementation of
                    national security policies by the several agencies” of the Federal Government.
                    As such, the Operations Coordinating Board was to be considered an adjunct of
                    and direct auxiliary to the National Security Council. Texts of the Executive
                    order and the White House press release are in Department of State <hi
                        rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, September 28, 1953, pages 420–421.</p>
                <p>The creation of the Operations Coordinating Board followed directly from
                    recommendations made to the President by his Committee on International
                    Information Activities in its report of June 30, 1953 (particularly in Chapter
                    7). The report is printed on <ref target="#pg_1795">page 1795</ref>.</p>
            </div>
